<subsection xml:id="subsection-1-3-3">
    <title>Limits at Infinity and Dominance</title>
    <p>
        Let's consider <m>\lim_{x\rightarrow \infty} \frac{x}{e^x}</m>.  
        How might we go about finding this limit?  
        We cannot use the basic rules given above.  
        For these kinds of limits (often called "indeterminate"), it is handy to have some rules established in calculus.  
        They can easily be proved using L'Hopital's rule.  
    </p>
</subsection>